nmental heritage, and the responsibility of governments - local, national or (in the unique case of Antarctica) international - to protect environments over which they exercise stewardship. Additionally, the presence of international commercial enterprises, especially marine and other mass transport modes, represent unique governance challenges.This book deals mainly with environmental issues and the management implications arising from polar tourism, one of the fastest-growing sectors of world tourism. However, many of the issues discussed here arise no less urgently in temperate and tropical wilderness areas, and indeed in any region where sensitive environments are subjected to mass tourism. The principles and guidelines discussed here are of interest and practical use in tourism studies generally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTourismxEnvironmental aspectszPolar regions. 0aTourismzPolar regions. 4aPolar regions. 4aTHE ENVIRONMENT. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aAntarctica tourism.  aArctic tourism.  aenvironmental heritage.  aenvironmental management.  aindigenous heritage.  apolar regions.  apolar tourism management.  apolar tourism.  asensitive wilderness areas .  awilderness tourism.1 aSnyder, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCVP eBook-Package Backfile 2000-2013z978311075437740uhttps://doi.org/10.21832/978184541147340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781845411473423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781845411473.jpg  a978-3-11-075437-7  CVP eBook-Package Backfile 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL